ogical Grammar -- t15. Towards Reflecting the Dynamic Nature of Grammar in Foreign Language Instruction: Expectations and Current Pedagogic Practice0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe volume consists of articles on issues relating to the morphosyntactic development of foreign language learners from different L1 backgrounds, in many cases involving languages which are typologically distant from English, such has Polish, Greek and Turkish. It highlights areas which may be expected to be especially transfer-prone at both the interlingual and intralingual levels. The articles in the first part report empirical studies on word morphology and sentence patterns and also look at the interface of lexis and grammar in the discourse and syntactic processing of foreign language learners. The second part elaborates on pedagogical issues concerning the acquisition of difficult grammatical features such as the English article system or the ‘s’ ending in the third person singular. It also comments more generally on the way pedagogic grammar functions in the learning of the L2.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxMorphosyntax. 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teaching. 0aSecond language acquisition. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Psycholinguistics.2bisacsh  aSLA.  aSecond Language Acquisition.  acrosslinguistic influence.  aforeign language learning.  amorphology .  amorphosyntactic development.  amorphosyntax.  asecond language learning.  asyntactic processing.  atransfer.1 aAltunkol, Esra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallies, Marcus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCan, Cem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l